<h2>Research</h2>

<p>
I am a member of
 the <a href="http://www.cs.bham.ac.uk/research/groupings/theory/">Theory
 group</a> (which include programming language research) at Birmingham
 and the Academic Centre of Excellence in Cyber Security Research
 (ACE-CSR).
</p>

<p>
My research interests are in  programming languages. Currently I am  particularly interested in:
</p>
<ul>
<li>Concurrency, such as rely-guarantee logic and linearizability</li>
<li>Substructural logics and types for programming languages, such as
linear and separation logic and Lambek calculus</li>
<li>Compiling, particularly CPS compiling or LLVM/clang</li>
<li>Using Agda for programming language semantics</li>
<li>Secure programming and memory safety</li>
<li>Program analysis for security</li>

<li><a href="research/parsing-regular-expressions.shtml">parsing and
regular expression matching</a> using semantic ideas
</li>

<li><a href="research/control-concurrency.shtml">control and concurrency</a> particularly in low-level language close to hardware or OS 
</li>

<li> Secure programming and software security, particularly in
conjunction with programming language design and technology.  
</li>

<li>Abstract machines (in the tradition of Landin's SECD machine)</li>

</ul>

<p>
There is a <a href="research/hayo-thielecke-publications.shtml">
page with my publications (all online)</a>.
</p>

<p>
If you are interested in studying for a PhD with me,
I would be happy to discuss possible <a href="phd-topics.html">PhD topics in
Programming Languages and Software Security</a>.
</p>

